Mark Anderson


Staff Writer
Sacramento Business Journal







 



 











 Enlarge





                BioConsortia CEO Marcus Meadows-Smith and senior vice president Susan Turner at the… more 

                BioConsortia Inc.            








 



A growing, Davis-based agriculture technology company has raised $8 million in new equity funding.
BioConsortia Inc. disclosed the fully subscribed funding round in an Oct. 26 filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission.













 Enlarge






                            BioConsortia CEO Marcus Meadows-Smith and senior vice president Susan Turner at the… more 
BioConsortia Inc.










 


The company has a pipeline of seed treatment and soil-delivered products that it's bringing to market. BioConsortia has patented technology for using beneficial groups of microbes to spur healthy soil growth around seeds, leading to higher yields in food crops, including soybeans, corn, wheat, rice, high-value fruit crops and vegetables.





BioConsortia previously raised $15 million in the spring of 2014, shortly before announcing that the company would move its headquarters to Davis in August of that year. That 2014 funding came from Khosla Ventures and Otter Capital LLC. The round was split equally between the two funds. Khosla Ventures is a Menlo Park-based venture capital fund headed by Sun Microsystems Inc. co-founder Vinod Khosla. Otter Capital is based in Palo Alto.
BioConsortia CEO Marcus Meadows-Smith was not available for comment.
Otter and Khosla didn’t return calls seeking comment on whether they also invested in this latest round.
Meadows-Smith is a former CEO of AgraQuest Inc., a Davis ag technology company that was acquired by Bayer CropScience for $425 million in 2012. Meadows-Smith was the CEO of AgraQuest for the four years leading up to the Bayer sale. Otter Capital had been an investor in AgraQuest.
BioConsortia was established in 2014 as the parent company to New Zealand-based BioDiscovery Ltd.
BioDiscovery, founded in 1994, made a breakthrough discovery in 2009 with an advanced microbial selection process, and got its first funding from Khosla.




 


Meadows-Smith has said that he moved BioConsortia's headquarters to Davis because the region is a hub of biological control research and innovation.

Mark Anderson covers agriculture, banking and finance, restaurants and hospitality for the Sacramento Business Journal.











 







